{{Shrine | Name = Kotai Jingū (皇大神宮) | image = {{image requested|cat=Osaka city}} | location = {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft}} {{ill|Osaka City|ja|大阪市|qq=draft}} {{ill|Joto Ward|ja|城東区|qq=draft}} {{ill|Imafuku Minami|ja|今福南|qq=draft}} 2-chome 12-31 | Latitude degrees = 34 | Latitude minutes = 41 | Latitude seconds = 51.7 | Longitude degrees = 135 | Longitude minutes = 33 | Longitude seconds = 3.1 | deity = {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照皇大御神|qq=draft}} | Shrine Rank = {{ill|Former Village Shrine|ja|旧村社|qq=draft}} | Founded = Unknown | Main hall = | Alias = {{Ublist| Imafuku Ebisu | Imafuku Kotai Jingū }} | Annual festival = {{Ublist| {{ill|April 22|ja|4月22日|qq=draft}} | {{ill|October 22|ja|10月22日|qq=draft}} }} | Map = Japan Osaka city }}
'''Kotai Jingū''' (皇大神宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Imafuku Minami|ja|今福南|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Joto Ward|ja|城東区|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka City|ja|大阪市|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft}}. It is affectionately known as "Imafuku Ebisu".
== History ==
The founding year is unknown<ref name="Osaka City">{{Cite web |url=https://www.city.osaka.lg.jp/joto/page/0000000740.html |title=皇大神宮 |publisher=Osaka City |accessdate=2024-08-15 |language=ja}}</ref>. It is said to have been established during the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft}} when {{ill|Kuki Imafuku Mikuriya|ja|久岐今福御厨|qq=draft}} was developed<ref name="Osaka City" />. Before the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft}} edict, it was known as the {{ill|Thirty Guardian Deities Shrine|ja|三十番神社|qq=draft}}. Under the modern shrine Ranking system, it was designated a village shrine, received accounting designation in 1911 ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft}} 44), and became a {{ill|Shinsen heihaku ryō kyōshinsha|ja|神饌幣帛供進社|qq=draft}} in 1912. In 1947 ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|qq=draft}} 22), it was removed from state control under the {{ill|Shintō Directive|ja|神道指令|qq=draft}}<ref name="Official">{{Cite web |url=https://koutaijingu.wixsite.com/mysite/blank-1 |title=由緒 |publisher=皇大神宮 |accessdate=2024-11-20 |language=ja}}</ref>.
The current shrine building was renovated in 1742 ({{ill|Kanpō era|ja|寛保|qq=draft}} 2), 1842 ({{ill|Tenpō era|ja|天保|qq=draft}} 13), and 1880 (Meiji 13), and reconstructed by {{ill|Furukawa Shigeharu|ja|古川重春|qq=draft}}, who designed {{ill|Osaka Castle|ja|大阪城|qq=draft}}, in 1932 (Shōwa 7)<ref name="Osaka City" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.osaka-jinjacho.jp/funai_jinja/dai4shibu/joto-ku/04006kotaijingu.html |title=皇大神宮 |publisher=Osaka Prefecture Shrine Office |accessdate=2024-08-15}}</ref>.
In the {{ill|Great Hanshin-Awaji Earthquake|ja|阪神・淡路大震災|qq=draft}} of 1995 (Heisei 7), part of the worship hall collapsed. It was repaired the following year with a copper roof replacing the previous tile roof.
The {{ill|Kinoshita Yōemon Land Survey Record|ja|木下与右衛門御検地帳|qq=draft}} (1594, Bunroku 3) states that the shrine was exempted from taxation on an area measuring 26 ken east to west and 17 ken north to south (1 tan, 4 se, 4 chōbu)<ref name="Official" />{{Sfn|Kimura|1971|p={{page needed|date=November 2024}}}}.
The stone guidepost at the southwest corner of the worship hall was erected in March 1833 (Tenpō 3) by six caretakers. Originally, it stood at the southeastern corner of the crossroads on the {{ill|Kotsutsumi Kaidō (Old Embankment Road)|ja|古堤街道|qq=draft}} (Yamato Road), a major route for pilgrimages to {{ill|Nozaki|ja|野崎|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōmine Mountain|ja|大峰山|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft}}. A local legend recounts that villagers danced wildly here during the {{ill|Okagemairi|ja|お蔭参り|qq=draft}} pilgrimage frenzy, and the guidepost was later moved to the shrine grounds{{Sfn|Kimura|1971|p={{page needed|date=November 2024}}}}. In March 1859 ({{ill|Ansei era|ja|安政|qq=draft}} 6), a lantern was added to the top of the guidepost by pilgrims from Imafuku village heading to Mount Ōmine. The guidepost reads:
"Left: Osaka Road. Right: Nozaki, Nara, Ise Road. Tōsonzan Pilgrimage Group."
Until the {{ill|Taishō era|ja|大正|qq=draft}} period, a sacred old enoki tree, over 1,000 years old, stood on the shrine grounds{{Sfn|Honda|1913|p={{page needed|date=November 2024}}}}.
The Imafuku Ebisu Shrine on the premises is known as "Imafuku Ebisu". The annual Ebisu Market held every January has continued since before {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|qq=draft}}<ref name="Osaka City" />.
The shrine grounds also host the {{ill|Kojirō Inari Shrine|ja|小女郎稲荷社|qq=draft}}, which is mentioned in Volume 3 of the '''{{ill|Settsu Meisho Zue|ja|摂津名所図会|qq=draft}}'''. This Inari shrine was originally located on {{ill|Kitsune-yama|ja|狐山|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Namazue Village|ja|鯰江村|qq=draft}}. It is considered one of the "Three Great Inari Shrines of Kansai", alongside {{ill|Genkurō Inari Shrine|ja|源九郎稲荷神社|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Shindōmori Kuzunoha Inari Shrine|ja|信太森葛葉稲荷神社|qq=draft}}<ref name="Osaka City" />.
== deity == * {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照皇大御神|qq=draft}}
