The Imafuku Ebisu Shrine on the premises is known as "Imafuku Ebisu". The annual Ebisu Market held every January has continued since before [[:en:World War II|World War II]]<ref name="Osaka City" />.
The shrine grounds also host the {{ill|Kojirō Inari Shrine|ja|小女郎稲荷社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojirō Inari Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 皇大神宮 (大阪市)}}, which is mentioned in Volume 3 of the '''{{ill|Settsu Meisho Zue|ja|摂津名所図会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Settsu Meisho Zue|qq=|1=Settsu Meisho Zue|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11498549}}'''. This Inari shrine was originally located on {{ill|Kitsune-yama|ja|狐山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kitsune-yama|qq=|1=Kitsune-yama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q119380142}} in {{ill|Namazue Village|ja|鯰江村|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Namazue Village|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 鯰江町|1=Namazue|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q48519631}}. It is considered one of the "Three Great Inari Shrines of Kansai", alongside {{ill|Genkurō Inari Shrine|ja|源九郎稲荷神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genkurō Inari Shrine|qq=|1=Genkurō Inari-jinja|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11563977}} and {{ill|Shindōmori Kuzunoha Inari Shrine|ja|信太森葛葉稲荷神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shindōmori Kuzunoha Inari Shrine|qq=|1=Shinodanomori Kuzunoha Inari Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11386029}}<ref name="Osaka City" />.
